
5d-Block Triple-Zeta Basis Set Archive
======================================


Date: 08 Dec 2011


When publishing work that uses these basis sets, please use the following citation:

K.G. Dyall, Theor. Chem. Acc. (2004) 112: 403; K. G. Dyall and A. S. P. Gomes, 
Theor. Chem. Acc. (2010) 125:97.
Basis sets are available from the Dirac web site, http://dirac.chem.sdu.dk.

For the 3d core correlating functions, please use the following citation:

K.G. Dyall, Theor. Chem. Acc. (2012) 131, 1217. DOI: 10.1007/s00214-012-1217-8. 
Basis sets are available from the Dirac web site, http://dirac.chem.sdu.dk.



This archive contains the exponents and the SCF spinor or orbital coefficients, 
given with respect to normalized (spherical or 2-spinor) Gaussian functions, for
the triple-zeta basis sets described in the above articles.  The contractions
are taken from SCF calculations on the configuration average of the d^n s^2 and 
d^n+1 s^1 configurations. 

The primitive basis set is a 30s 24p 15d 10f set, including functions for the 6p.
This set supersedes the earlier 29s 24p 15d 10f set. In the current set the s set
has been augmented and reoptimized, the d set has been reoptimized on the
configuration average of the d^n s^2 and d^n+1 s^1 configurations, and the p and
f sets also reoptimized. 

NOTE: Functions are counted from the function with the smallest exponent to the largest. 

The SCF exponent sets were generated as follows:

* Optimization of the s, p, d, and f sets separately, on the total energy of the
  configuration average of the d^n s^2 and d^n+1 s^1 configurations
* Addition of 3 exponents for the 6p, optimized with reoptimization of the
  exponents for the 3p-5p outer antinodes on the total energy of the d^n s^2
  configuration
* Replacement of the outer SCF f exponent with the two 5d/6s correlating f
  exponents and reoptimization of the other 8 f exponents.

In all the following descriptions, this is the set referred to as the SCF 
exponent set. 

The correlating exponents were generated as follows

* A 2f1g set for the 5d and 6s was optimized in MR-SDCI calculations on the
  ground configuration.
* A 2g1h set for the 4f was optimized in MR-DCI calculations on the ground
  configuration, with double excitations from the 4f shell into the correlating
  orbitals coupled to J=0.
* A g function for 3d correlation was optimized in MR-DCI calculations on the
  ground configuration, with double excitations from the 3d shell into the 
  correlating spinors, coupled to J=0. A 2f1g set was used for the correlating
  space, with the 2f exponents taken from the occupied set and frozen while the
  g exponent was optimized.

The exponents for 5d dipole polarization were generated as follows:

* The f set was extended in an even-tempered fashion to produce an f exponent
  for dipole polarization. The ratio used to obtain this f exponent was applied
  to the g correlating exponent to obtain a g exponent for dipole polarization.

The contractions are taken from SCF calculations on the weighted average of
the d^n s^2, d^n+1 s^1, and d^n p^2 configurations with weight ratio
45%:45%:10%, except for Hg, where the d^n s^2 and d^n p^2 configurations are
used with weight ratio 90%:10%.

The archive is set out as follows.

1. Exponents and SCF coefficients for Dirac-Hartree-Fock wave functions, in order
   of Z. The large component functions are given first, followed by the small 
   component functions. Both components are labelled with the large component
   symmetry type, but the primitive functions for the small component are
   those obtained by restricted kinetic balance from the large component.
   The spin-orbit components have a "-" label for j=l-1/2 and a "+" label for
   j=l+1/2.

2. Exponents and SCF coefficients for spin-free modified Dirac-Hartree-Fock wave
   functions, in order of Z. The large component functions are given first, 
   followed by the pseudo-large component functions, then the Foldy-Wouthuysen
   transformed large component functions. Note that all components have the same
   symmetry type. 

3. Exponents of valence dipole polarization functions.

4. Exponents of valence correlating functions. The f functions are included in
   the SCF set.

5. Exponents of core correlating functions.


Basis set construction.
----------------------

Contracted basis sets can be constructed by adding primitive functions to the SCF 
set. These basis sets are described below. Note that the term "triple zeta" applies 
to the s and p set, and the d set is quadruple zeta. This is a result of keeping a 
reasonable energy balance for the basis sets. Functions are counted in increasing
exponent size, from the smallest.


NOTE: Functions are counted in increasing exponent size, from the smallest to the largest.

The valence space is defined here as the 5d, 6s, and 6p orbitals. 

1. Valence flexibility. To the SCF functions, add the following:

   1st and 3rd s primitives from the SCF set 
   1st and 2nd p primitives from the SCF set 
   1st, 2nd, and 3rd d primitives from the SCF set
   1st and 2nd f primitives from the SCF set (valence correlating f functions)
   Valence correlating g function

2. Valence + outer core. This set adds the outer-core correlation from the 5s and 5p
   shells. To set 1, add the following functions: 

   4th and 6th s primitives from the SCF set 
   4th and 6th p primitives from the SCF set 
   4th d primitive from the SCF set
   3rd f primitive from the SCF set

   If linear dependence is encountered in the d set, use the 1st, 2nd, and 4th
   primitives from the SCF set for valence flexibility, and add the 5th SCF
   primitive for outer core flexibility.


3. Valence + outer core + 4f. This set adds correlation from the 4f shell.  To set 2,
   add the following functions: 

   7th and 9th s primitives from the SCF set 
   7th and 8th p primitives from the SCF set 
   5th d primitive from the SCF set 
   4th f primitive from the SCF set
   Correlating 2g1h functions for 4f correlation

4. Inner core correlation. Add the correlating g function to the basis sets for the
   n=3 shell, and uncontract two s, p, d, and f functions.For 2s2p and 1s correlation,
   uncontract 2d1f and 2p1d, respectively. The uncontracted functions should be
   chosen to span the radial maxima of the shells. 

5. Dipole polarization of the 5d. To any of the above basis sets, add the polarizing
   f and g functions.
